5 TOWN OF MAIDEN
6 SECTION 7.(a) Section 4 of the Charter of the Town of Maiden, being Chapter 103
7 of the Private Laws of 1883, as amended by Chapter 445 of the 1955 Session Laws, Town
8 Ordinance No. 3-76 adopted on April 5, 1976, and Ordinance No. 11-2006 adopted on April 3,
9 2006, reads as rewritten:
10 "Section 4. Elections.
11 …
12 (b) Elections shall be conducted on the first Tuesday of November in odd-numbered
13 even-numbered years as provided by the Laws of North Carolina.
14 (c) Election of the Mayor and Council shall be on a nonpartisan plurality basis and the
15 following rules shall be utilized in determining those elected: (1) When more than one person is
16 seeking election to a single office, the candidate who receives the highest number of votes shall
17 be declared elected. (2) When more persons are seeking election to two or more offices
18 (constituting a group) than there are offices to be filled, those candidates receiving the highest
19 number of votes equal in number to the number of offices to be filled, shall be declared elected.
20 (3) If two or more candidates receiving the highest number of votes each receive the same number
21 of votes, the board of elections shall determine the winner by lot.results determined in accordance
22 with G.S. 163-292. Except as otherwise provided, the elections for the Town of Maiden shall be
23 held and conducted in accordance with the uniform municipal election laws in Chapter 163 of
24 the General Statutes.
25 (d) The term of office for the Mayor shall be two (2) years.
26 (e) The term of office for the Council shall be determined as follows: (1) Election in 1975 to
27 provide that the two candidates receiving the first and second largest number of votes to serve
28 four-year terms; (2) Election in 1975 to provide that the three candidates receiving the third,
29 fourth, and fifth largest number of votes to serve two-year terms; (3) Election in 1977 to provide
30 that the two candidates receiving the first and second largest number of votes to serve four-year
31 terms; (4) Election in 1977 to provide that the candidate receiving the third largest number of
32 votes to serve a two-year term; (5) Election in all odd-numbered years after 1977 to provide that
33 staggered such that during the regular municipal election in each even-numbered year, three
34 council members shall be elected with the two candidates receiving the first and second largest
35 number of votes to serve four-year terms; terms and the candidate receiving the third largest
36 number of votes to serve a two-year term."
37 SECTION 7.(b) No municipal elections shall be conducted in the Town of Maiden
38 in 2027. The terms of office for the mayor and two council members in the Town of Maiden
39 serving on the effective date of this section whose terms are set to expire in 2027 shall be
40 extended by one year. The terms of office for three council members in the Town of Maiden
41 serving on the effective date of this section whose terms are set to expire in 2029 shall be
42 extended by one year. Regular municipal elections in the Town of Maiden shall resume in
43 even-numbered years beginning in 2028 with the same staggering of terms as when elections
44 were conducted in the odd-numbered years.
